  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in the United States and in many other jurisdictions around the world. It is a serious criminal offense that involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\"). This is typically done by funneling the money through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under federal law, specifically under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Penalties for money laundering can include substantial fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture. The severity of the penalties often depends on the amount of money involved and the specific circumstances of the case.\n\nFederal penalties for money laundering can include:\n- **Up to 20 years in prison** for each money laundering offense.\n- **Fines** of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\nsee usc title 18. In addition to federal laws, many states also have their own money laundering statutes that can lead to additional penalties.\n\nIt's important to note that money laundering is often associated with other crimes, such as drug trafficking, fraud, or organized crime, which can lead to even more severe legal consequences.",
